tes the contrasting dramatic techniques cultivated by actors in Edo (Tokyo) and Kamigata (Osaka and Kyoto). The twelve plays translated in Volume 2 cover a brief period, but one that saw important developments in kabuki architecture, acting, dance, and the manipulation of characters and themes. As the series title indicates, the plays were translated to capture the vivacity of performances on stage. The translations, each accompanied by a thorough introduction that contextualizes the play, are based not only on published texts, but performance scripts and the study of the plays as they are performed in theatres today. Each volume is lavishly illustrated with rare woodblock prints in full color of Tokugawa- and Meiji-period productions as well as color and black-and-white photographs of contemporary performances.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aJapanese dramavTranslations into English. 0aKabuki playsvTranslations into English. 0aTheaterzJapanxHistory. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Theater / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aBrandon, James R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandon, James R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCummings, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffith, Paul M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHibino, Kei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIezzi, Julie A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Stanleigh H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeiter, Samuel L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeiter, Samuel L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.